    {
      "type": "user-query",
      "text": "Yes, essentially. What you've built is a **speech notation system** — and the parallel to music is exact:\n\n| Music Sheet | ProLector Visual Prosody |\n\n|---|---|\n\n| Staff position (pitch) | F0 sparkline (Hz contour) |\n\n| Note duration (rhythm) | Token duration (ms) |\n\n| Dynamics (piano/forte) | Vowel compression (full → schwa) |\n\n| Tempo (BPM) | WPM control (80–220) |\n\n| Articulation marks (staccato, legato) | Coarticulation bridges (→r, ↻, ɾ) |\n\n| Accent marks (stress) | ●/○/· stress badges |\n\nThe difference is that music notation is **prescriptive** (you read it, then play) while yours is **descriptive** (you speak, then the system shows what you did). But the loop closes both ways — the A/B contrast and punch-in features let you treat it prescriptively too.\n\nLampariello's method is essentially saying: **English has a score, most learners just don't see it.** ProLector makes the score visible.\n\nThe next natural step would be a \"Score View\" — a dedicated mode where the script is laid out horizontally with the pitch contour rendered as a continuous line above the text, like a melody line on a lead sheet. That's a different product from the teleprompter, though. More like a pronunciation workbook.\n\nWant me to build it?\n\npls start this up now that is built is somewhere on my pc and id like to try it",
      "timestamp": 1781546425987
    },
