    {
      "type": "answer",
      "text": "Honestly? No. Looking at the screenshot:\n\n- **\"Primary stress ● / Secondary stress ○ / Unstressed ·\"** — linguistics jargon\n- **\"Full vowel / Compressed / Reduced / Schwa\"** — phonetics terms most adults don't know\n- **\"Linking R / Intrusion / Flap T\"** — IPA terminology\n- **Raw Hz values (230, 190, 180)** — meaningless without training\n\nA 15-year-old would see a wall of symbols and numbers and bounce.\n\n**What would actually work for a teen:**\n\n| Current | Simplified |\n|---------|-----------|\n| ●/○/· stress badges | 👆 **LOUD** / regular / quick |\n| \"Schwa\" / \"Reduced\" | **mumbled** (greyed out text) |\n| Hz pitch numbers | A **wavy line** that goes up = excited, down = calm |\n| Coarticulation icons (→r, ↻, ɾ) | **\"run-together\"** label with a little arrow |\n| \"Sub-ten-millisecond latency\" | Remove entirely — they don't care |\n\nWant me to add a **\"Simple Mode\"** toggle that strips the jargon and shows plain-English labels instead? Or rewrite the whole view to be teen-friendly by default?",
      "timestamp": 1781547006646
    },
    {
      "type": "thought",
      "text": "The user is asking if a 15-year-old would understand this interface. Looking at the screenshot, I can see it's quite technical with lots of linguistic terminology (Primary stress, Secondary stress, Unstressed, Full vowel, Compressed, Reduced, Schwa, Linking R, Intrusion, Flap T) and numerical pitch values (230, 190, 180, etc.). \n\nA 15-year-old learning English pronunciation would likely find this overwhelming. The interface needs to be simplified with:\n1. Plain language explanations\n2. Visual cues that are intuitive\n3. Less jargon\n4. Maybe a \"beginner mode\" or tutorial\n\nLet me suggest some simplifications and offer to implement them.",
